Smokers have a significantly increased risk of losing their teeth early.
This is evidenced by the long-term study of an international research team, including several employees of the German Institute for Nutritional Research (DIfE) in Potsdam.
Compared to non-smokers, smokers were at risk of losing their teeth prematurely to 2.5 to 3.6 times higher.
The researchers had observed more than 23,300 participants.
The main causes of tooth failure are caries and inflammation of the gums, the DIfE emphasizes.
For this periodontitis, smoking is a risk factor, the authors emphasize.
Therefore, the relationship between smoking and tooth loss is due to more frequent tooth inflammation in smokers.
It is not clear to what extent smoking also increases the risk of caries.
People who quit smoking could reduce their risk, but within a short period of time, the researchers write in the Journal of Dental Research.
However, it could take more than ten years for the danger to fall back to non-smokers, said first author Thomas Dietrich of the University of Birmingham in England.
