Europe’s refugee crisis: Hungary declares emergency, closes border, holds refugees back
Hungary declared the state of emergency and set off the southern border with Serbia on Tuesday and detained all those who tried to enter the country illegally, all with the aim of stopping the influx of migrants.
Chaos followed at the border, when hundreds of migrants gathered in a nobody’s country and Serbian officials reacted with indignation.
The people who had fled from violence stood for an unknown time in a strip of land on the road between the two control points of the countries and built tents and settled there.
But frustrations increased.
As a police helicopter floated over them, the migrants chanted "Open the Border!" and shouted insults against the Hungarian preparedness police.
Some have withdrawn food and water from protests.
Serbia’s foreign minister said it was “unacceptable” that migrants would be sent back from Hungary as more and more arrived from Macedonia and Greece.
(Serbia) wants to be part of the solution and not a collateral damage.
Talks with Brussels and other countries must take place in the coming days," said Ivica Dacic in Prague.
The turbulence at the Hungarian-Serbian border came a day after the 28-nation bloc could not agree on a common immigration policy at a disputed meeting in Brussels.
However, the ministers agreed to share the responsibility for 40,000 people seeking refuge in overcrowded Italy and Greece, and expressed their hope that finally - next month or by the end of the year - an agreement would be reached that the EU would take another 120,000 refugees, including some from UN.
German Chancellor Angela Merkel and Austria called for a special European Union summit on Tuesday to discuss the continent’s immigration crisis.
Hungary, however, did not put its hopes on a soon-to-be action by Brussels or its neighbours.
The state of emergency in two southern regions on Tuesday gave authorities more powers to cope with the crisis, enabling them to block roads and accelerate asylum procedures.
Hungarian Foreign Minister Peter Szijjarto said his country is also planning to build a barbed wire fence along its border to Romania to stop the influx of migrants through the country - after it finished a fence at the Serbian border.
CBS News correspondent Charlie D'Agata reported that even inmates were employed in the race to create the barbed wire fence between Hungary and Serbia.
In recent months, for many refugees from Syria and elsewhere in the Middle East, Hungary has become a significant passport and a point of entry into the European Union.
However, Prime Minister Viktor Orban has insisted that most of the upcoming economic refugees are looking for a better life, and not refugees who are entitled to protection - an opinion that strongly contradicts other EU countries, including Germany.
The new laws, which came into force at midnight in Hungary, make crossing the border or damaging the 4-metre (13-foot) high fence that the government had built along the southern border to Serbia a crime. These laws also impose higher penalties for detainees.
“Due to the situation created by mass migration, the Hungarian government declares the state of emergency,” government spokesman Zoltan Kovac told reporters in the southern city of Szeged.
We say it very clearly: illegal border crossing is a crime.
Parliament still has to agree procedurally to the military's deployment, which is expected for next week, but Associated Press reporters have seen heavily armed soldiers with vehicles and dogs at the border for days.
Gyorgy Bakondi, the country’s security adviser for Orban, said authorities had cleared 45 people while trying to cross the border, while 15 others had already penetrated deeper into the country.
They come across by damaging the fence, they are now in police custody and are accused of committing crimes under the new laws.
Authorities are about to repair the fence quickly.
Hungarian officials also closed two of the seven border crossings with Serbia on Tuesday morning after a railroad train had arrived to close the borders.
Chaos encircled the main border crossing near Roszke, Hungary, when the Hungarians opened a small office in a metal container to process people’s data and pushed a crowd to push into it.
About 20 were able to enter, but thousands were left out.
Another group of migrants blocked the main highway connection between Serbia and Hungary, saying they would refuse food and water until they were allowed to enter Hungary.
Election 2016: Hillary Clinton’s lead over Bernie Sanders cuts in national poll
Former U.S. Secretary of State Hillary Clinton continues to hold a two-digit lead in the democratic race for the nomination at the national level, but Senator Bernie Sanders wins against her on the ground.
Clinton now has the support of 47 percent of the democratic voters in the pre-election (58 percent before), while Sanders is in second place, with 27 percent (increase by 17 percent).
Vice President Joe Biden, who has not yet announced whether he is running for president, receives 15 percent of the Democratic voters in the election.
More than five months before the start of the election, most democratic voters say it is too early to say that their opinion is determined which candidates they will support.
But Clinton’s supporters are more resilient in their choice than those of the other candidates.
Since the CBS News poll, Clinton has lost to a number of demographic groups, while Sanders has made some profits.
Clinton holds a big lead in women and moderates, but these advances have diminished.
Their support for the men has fallen significantly, and Sanders is only 5 points behind this.
Clinton’s advantage for democratic voters under 50 has been distracted, and she and Sanders are now on the same level.
However, Clinton still has a big lead among the older voters.
Last month, Clinton was ahead of Sanders with a two-digit lead in the Liberals, but Sanders now has a 5-point lead in this group.
Approximately half of the Democratic voters in the nationwide election said they would enthusiastically support Clinton if she were nominated by the party.
A quarter would support her with some reservations and another 15 percent would only support her because she is the candidate.
Six percent would not support them.
Perhaps it is not surprising that Clinton’s current supporters are especially enthusiastic about her.
The views are more mixed with those who currently don’t support Clinton—only about a quarter would enthusiastically support her.
While 48 percent of Democratic voters in the polls say they support Clinton with enthusiasm, fewer Republican voters say this over their top candidate Donald Trump (35 percent).
When Clinton’s supporters are asked in an open question why they want her to be the candidate, the most common answer is that she has the right experience (16%), followed by the view that it’s time for a woman to become president (13%) and that she is the best candidate for the Job.
Clinton’s supporters also mention their connection to Bill Clinton (9 percent).
Consent to dealing with the problems and the eligibility are also cited.
As the vice president throws potential for the presidential office into the balance sheet, 57 percent of the Democratic voters want to see him in the race — although a third believe he shouldn’t.
If democratic voters are asked who would be their second choice for the party, Biden is at the top.
More than half of Clinton’s supporters say Biden would be their second choice far ahead of Sanders.
If Biden decides not to run for the Democratic nomination, Hillary Clinton’s lead rises from 20 points with Biden in the race to 30 points without him in the race.
Fifty-five percent of democratic voters see Clinton as the candidate with the best chances of winning the election, but this number has fallen from 78 percent in the past month.
Biden is by far a second in this measurement, but the percentage that sees him as the "most selectable" has increased.
However, when asked what is more important for a candidate, Democratic voters raise questions about eligibility.
Like last month, no single Democratic candidate or potential candidate for these voters stands out as unacceptable.
Democratic candidates or potential candidates deliver good results in some of the key features of their party’s pre-election voters.
The majority consider Clinton, Sanders, and Biden to be honest and trustworthy and equipped with strong leadership qualities.
Biden is best off the three candidates with honesty, while Clinton's strength is the lead.
Thirty percent of Democratic voters don’t believe Clinton is honest and trustworthy, twice as many say that about Sanders (15 percent), but 27 percent don’t have an opinion about him.
Democratic voters of the pre-election generally also see Clinton, Sanders and Biden ideologically in line with their views.
In all of these measures, about a quarter of the democratic voters have no opinion of Sanders.
As questions about Hillary Clinton’s use of a personal email address and a server continue to be asked during her tenure as foreign minister, most Democratic voters in the pre-election are satisfied with her statement of the matter and say that it has not influenced her opinions at all.
But it is a different story in the American public as a whole.
Half of Americans are now dissatisfied with their statement, while only about a third are satisfied.
The public opinion on this was split in March, shortly after the problem came to light.
Most Americans said the email controversy had no impact on their general opinions of Clinton, although 36 percent said their opinion of her had deteriorated further.
There are mostly Republicans, more than six out of 10, who say their views of Clinton have gotten worse.
Although Clinton is seen by her party’s voters as honest and trustworthy, this is still a problem for them overall among registered voters: only 32 percent see them as honest and trustworthy, eight percent less than last month, and 15 points less since May.
62 percent of voters do not consider them to be an honest and trustworthy person.
At the same time, 55 percent of voters across the country also see Trump as dishonest and unreliable.
However, Clinton and Trump are getting good grades in leadership.
Of the six candidates tested, Biden, Carson and Bush cut off best in honesty.
A majority considers Sanders to be more than honest, but as with Carson, many have no opinion of him.
