Five members of the fraternity charged with the death of a Baruch college student
Almost two years after a student died during a chilling ritual of a student union in Pocono Mountains, Pennsylvania, murder charges are filed against five people.
Members of the New York Baruch College Pi-Delta Psi Brotherhood attacked Chun "Michael" Deng brutally during an introductory ritual in September 2013 and delayed his transport to the hospital, which contributed to his death, police said.
Officials said he had been loaded with a 30-pound backpack full of sand with his eyes, and repeatedly attacked while trying to reach a target over a frozen field.
Mr. Deng finally complained of headaches, then he fell unconscious.
The members of the Pi-Delta Psi Brotherhood did not call 911 after Deng became powerless and allegedly waited an hour before taking him to a hospital, police said.
However, they had time to change their clothes, google their symptoms, and contact Andy Meng, the national president of the Brotherhood, to seek advice, police chief Chris Wagner said at a press conference.
“At this point, the members started hiding utensils and put the brotherhood’s well-being above that of Michael Deng,” Wagner said.
He could not be resurrected, and he died the next morning of his injuries.
According to an autopsy report, Deng was repeatedly injured with stupendous force to the head, thigh and thigh.
"Too many families have been destroyed by the Schikanes of the Brotherhood. At least one student has died from the Schikanes every year since 1970," Douglas Fierberg, a lawyer representing Deng's family, said in a statement.
Brotherhoods and their members need to be held accountable, and this step by authorities is very important.
A Monroe County Grand Jury recommended a third-degree murder charge for the first five members.
Thirty-two members of the fraternity, including Mr Meng, are also charged with schismary attacks and the formation of a criminal association.
“We want not only to hold the people involved accountable, but if there is an organization that has officially or unofficially sanctioned this, then we will also blame them,” Wagner said at a press conference on Tuesday.
The Baruch College has banned the fraternity, and the national fraternity has revoked its membership in the local group.
This will happen when the Fed raises interest rates.
An increase in interest rates is coming, and the house will fall into disrepair, yields for bonds will rise, and the economy will slip into a recession.
We know that.
What we don’t know is how long it will take and how long it will last.
In particular, the history of the economy provides little guidance on how to proceed.
A recession came within just 11 months after the first interest rate increase and lasted 86 months.
The Federal Reserve’s aggressiveness in raising interest rates is often, if not always, a factor in how the economy and financial institutions react.
That is why representatives of the U.S. Central Bank have so strongly stressed that investors should not focus on when they start raising interest rates, but rather on the period needed for normalization.
In fact, several variables play a role.
In the end, however, market participants could find that the whole excitement may have been exaggerated due to an increase in interest rates.
"The first increase in the Fed since the global financial crisis will inevitably be interpreted by some as a signal for the end of the era of 'cheap money'," Julian Jessop, chief economist at Capital Economics, said in a statement to customers.
On the contrary, we do not expect the gradual return of U.S. interest rates to normal levels, but still to low levels to lead to a seismic shock that many seem to fear.
However, this does not mean that there will be no impact.
Here’s a look at how some sectors of the economy could react based on historical trends:
As the market saw last month, preventing interest rate increases can make things volatile for a while.
As soon as the increase occurs, the influence is not so dramatic.
“There seems to be a tendency that wealth returns will be depreciated 12 to 24 months after the first increase, which may again reflect the delay in monetary policy,” German-Bank analysts said in a recent study on what happens after the Fed’s interest rate increases.
More specifically, the market has been mostly in the uptrend in the last 35 years - about 14 percent - on the way to interest rate increases, rather flat in the 250 days following (average gain of 2.6 percent), then back to the normal state of 500 days, with a bar rate of 14 percent, the average rate of returns in Doene set.
The Deutsche Bank said that the impact on the shares tends to occur later in the increase cycle and returns begin to decline.
Recessions are a fact of economic life, but interest rates increases often promote them.
In the current case, the Fed is facing some conditions that previously did not exist and that could accelerate a recession.
It is particularly noteworthy that the gross domestic product will be near its lowest point at an interest rate increase of the Fed.
According to Deutsche Bank, the 118 interest rate increases since 1950 were only twice the nominal GDP below 4.5 percent.
Although the second quarter of 2015 was 3.6 percent, few expect this to continue and expect only 1.5 percent for the third quarter, according to the Atlanta Fed.
Increases in interest rates in such a fragile economic landscape could be risky and raise the question of whether it is different this time,” Deutsche Bank said.
Market participants have decided to raise interest rates by the Fed all year round, and all eyes were on the Federal Open Market Committee meeting this week, which ends on Thursday.
While many strategists and economists believe that the FOMC could approve an increase in this session, futures trading indicates only a 25 percent likelihood.
“In our study, all of the increase cycles from 1950 to today have taken place in a super cycle with increasing GDP swings and pre-recession rises very quickly after the start of recovery,” the report said.
In contrast, this is a clearly slow recovery from what was the worst recession in the observed phase.
The current cycle is by far the longest awaited by the Fed since the end of the last recession; the record was 35 months, and this is 74 months so far.
Fixed income was also volatile as the market anticipates an interest rate increase, and the pattern is quite similar to that of the capital market.
The main difference is that the effect on bonds is faster than on stocks when they change their strategic course.
For bonds, the returns seem to change the direction as soon as the first increase/decrease occurs in the cycle.
At the end of the increase cycle, bond earnings fell immediately, Deutsche Bank said.
The strategists of Charles Schwab believe that the rise in interest rates will lead to yields between longer and shorter bonds shrinking closer and lead to a flattening of the curve.
High-interest bonds often bring better yields in such a climate, although “we are still cautious to expect higher yields,” said Kathy Jones, fixed-income analyst at Schwab, in an analysis.
Interestingly, Jones believes that the markets have already adjusted to Fed strategy ratings.
"In addition to the strength of the dollar and the decline in inflation expectations, there are some indications that the market has adapted to the prospect of stricter monetary policy," she wrote.
Short-term interest rates have increased, the yield curve is flat, credit spans have expanded and volatility has increased - all features of the market as the Fed tightens its strategy.
Overall, companies that do most of their business in the U.S. will benefit as interest rates rise and local products become more attractive.
Multinational companies with high debts will get worse as a rising dollar makes their products more expensive on the global market and also the financing of their debts.
“The story shows that quality shares tend to respond extremely positively three months after an initial interest rate increase,” Goldman Sachs analysts said in a report for customers.
Companies with strong balance sheets have exceeded on average 5 percentage points after each of the interest increases in 1994, 1999 and 2004.
Companies with high capital returns and low volatility in their shares also outperform their low quality pendants by an average of 4 (percentage points) and 3 (percentage points) respectively.
Debt will be a big problem.
Companies with a high share of flexible interest rates will lose the most, Goldman said.
Outside of the pure stock games, consumers will also benefit from the rising dollar.
Savers could see profits through higher returns, even if experts disagree how quickly this will take place.
