'Sonogenetics' Can Control Brain Cells Through Sound Waves
The video shows how the nematodes change the direction at the moment they are irradiated with sound pulses.
Scientists have grown worms with genetically modified nervous systems that can be controlled by outbreaks of sound waves.
The tiny nematodes change the direction at the moment they are irradiated with sound pulses that have too high frequencies for the human ear to be heard.
The pulses work by switching on Motoneuron cells that are genetically modified to carry the membrane channels that respond to ultrasound waves.
Researchers Reading and Writing Brain Activity with Light
The researchers said the worms showed the power of a new procedure called sonogenetics, where ultrasound can be used to activate a number of brain, heart, and muscle cells outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute in La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that the procedure could one day replace deep-brain stimulation, an invasive procedure that electrical impulses into people’s brains to treat symptoms of Parkinson’s disease.
Threadworms usually do not respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that they did it when surrounded by a liquid with microscopic air bubbles.
The bubbles, he found out, amplifie the ultrasound waves, which then penetrate the worms.
The amplified ultrasound waves act on structures called TRP-4 ion channels and are found in the membranes of some of the worm cells.
The sound waves cause the opening of these ion channels and activate the cells to which they are assigned, according to a report by Nature Communications.
To create ultrasound-controlled nematodes, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motor neurons carry TRP-4 ion channels.
When he applies ultrasound to the altered creatures, the sound waves are amplified by the microbubbles and transferred to the worms, where they turn on the altered motor neurons.
The process has some similarities to optogenetics, a groundbreaking tool that allows scientists to turn on and off neurons with light pulses.
But Chalasani said that sonogenetics could have some advantages over this technique.
Unlike light, which must be sent down to the desired location in the brain at an optical fiber, low-frequency ultrasonic wave tissue can pass unhindered and can thus be sent to the brain from above on the skull.
“We believe that with gene therapy and a therapeutic virus it is possible to make the targeted human neurons temporarily susceptible to the ultrasound signal in a clinical setting for certain neurological treatments,” said Chalasani.
Other applications could focus on muscle cells and insulin-producing cells, he added.
