For lightly overweight diabetics, weight loss surgery can be helpful.
The benefits of weight loss surgery for lightly overweight people with type 2 diabetes can last at least five years after a new study.
It’s still too early to say whether people with mild obesity live longer after weight loss surgery than those who receive non-surgical treatments.
“The mortality data takes a long time to show something,” said Dr. Robin Blackstone, an expert in weight loss surgery who wrote a guide article on the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Weight loss surgeries or obesity surgery, use various methods to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce hunger and limit the body’s ability to absorb food.
Over the years, obesity surgeries have proven effective in treating type 2 diabetes, but most studies have been conducted in people who are obese with a body mass index (BMI) of 35 or higher.
BMI, a certain degree of weight in terms of size, is considered normal between 18.5 and 24.9.
A BMI of 25 or more indicates that someone is overweight, and people with a BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers from Taiwan's Min-Sheng General Hospital used data they have collected in a study since 2007, comparing two types of obesity surgery - gastric bypass and gastric tube formation - to medical treatments for type 2 diabetes in people who were mildly overweight.
The average BMI among those who underwent this surgery decreased from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year in this study.
Meanwhile, BMI remained approximately the same in those who received non-surgical diabetes treatments at 29.
Among those who underwent surgery, 36% fully resolved diabetes and 28% partially.
In the medical-treated group, compared to this, diabetes resolved completely in only one percent and in part in only about two percent.
In addition, the results in the controls of blood pressure, triglycerides and "bad" LDL cholesterol were "generally better in the 'surgical' group", the authors found.
The researchers also monitor patients' blood levels of hemoglobin A1c, which reflects blood sugar levels over time.
Hemoglobin A1c is best kept below 7 percent, the researchers write.
After surgery, the average hemoglobin A1c level decreased from about 9 percent to about 6 percent.
However, in the medical therapy group, it remained stable at about 8 percent.
But this better "glycaemic control" - as reflected in the improved hemoglobin A1c level - did not reduce mortality in five years, according to lead researcher Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared average results for the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, the bypass surgery group had more weight loss (18.7 vs. 14.2 kg) compared to the gastrectomy group, achieved greater declines in BMI (7.4 vs. 5.1) and hemoglobin A1c (3.1% vs. 2.1%), and had more than 16% of the above, and had a total loss of 16%.
While the new study does not show any survival benefit of surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study of heavier people in Sweden that surgery leads to a longer life, says Blackstone of the University of Arizona, College of Medicine Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent obesity surgery were about 29 percent less likely to die over the course of 15 years — compared to a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study showed no benefit for survival in surgical patients, Blackstone said it was reassuring for people with a BMI under 35 who are interested in the procedure.
“This is the critical point of this study because it says this operation is lower in this lower BMI group,” without an increased risk of death or kidney disease, she said.
Blackstone added that people and their doctors should start taking weight seriously as soon as the patient with his BMI is between 27 and 30.
"I think we'll wait too long until we get people to take this seriously," she said.
I think once they have accumulated these genetic changes that have strongly linked their bodies to obesity and diabetes, a reversal is really hard.”
