Robot cars: government wants to be a pioneer for Germany
Germany is expected to be a technological pioneer in changing the car at the will of the German government.
The Federal Cabinet decided on Wednesday a strategy paper from the house of Transport Minister Alexander Dobrindt (CSU), which provides for investments in the development of digital infrastructure, among other things.
Dobrindt spoke on Wednesday in Frankfurt on the outskirts of the IAA Automesse about a "new age of mobility".
Automated and networked driving will increase traffic safety and reduce traffic blockage, Dobrindt said.
He also wants to discuss the issue with his colleagues from the G7 countries, who will also meet with industry representatives at the IAA.
The Ministry of Transport’s strategy paper underlines, among other things, the importance of mobile broadband expansion and a rapid transition to digital audio.
A test track is currently being developed for testing new technology on Highway 9 in Bavaria.
In order for the driver "to be charged no additional liability risks", the federal government wants to "review the legal framework conditions and, where necessary, adapt to the new developments".
For example, Germany intends to work internationally to increase the permissible maximum speed for self-driving cars from 10 to 130 kilometres per hour.
In addition, the Federal Government is committed to an amendment to the Vienna Convention, which so far only provides for people as drivers.
In the case of automated driving, the car is increasingly taking the lead, the driver becomes more and more the passenger.
The technology is mainly based on sensors and cameras that capture the environment and process the data in seconds.
According to a study submitted by the Ministry of Economy, highly automated driving on highways will be technically possible by 2020.
However, driverless vehicles on public roads are "first to be expected far after 2020".
The value added in the field of driver assistance systems and highly automated driving functions at Germany’s location is estimated by the authors of the study to be around 8.4 billion euros for 2025.
"The digital networking of the car can lead to more safety and efficiency in road traffic," SPD traffic policymaker Sören Bartol said.
However, the issue of liability in the event of accidents and the security of the driver’s personal data must be clearly clarified.
However, Germans still see self-driving cars skeptical - much more than French or Americans.
A survey by the Forsa Institute on behalf of the test organisation Dekra, presented on Wednesday at the AA, concludes that only 8 percent of Germans believe that autonomous cars will be implemented in the next 10 years, 32 percent do not expect it to be over 20 years.
In France, 21 percent of respondents expect autonomous cars by 2025, while in the US, 33 percent.
Nonetheless, drivers in Germany are not yet ready to rely completely on a self-driving vehicle.
According to a survey by the digital association Bitkom, only seven percent would agree to give up control over the entire ride on all roads.
On the highway, that could be 15 percent in the flowing traffic, in the stall 45 percent.
Nearly one in four would not leave the car under any circumstances.
