EU wants to double mercury limit in predators
The European Commission wants to double the limits for mercury in large predators, thereby limiting a significantly higher dose of nerve poisoning to consumers.
The consumer organisation Foodwatch, which presents a relevant EU working paper, sharply criticized the plans: “The risks and side effects of missing industrial and environmental policies are being communicated with full zeal to pregnant and young children,” explained Matthias Wolfschmidt of Foodwatch.
According to Wolfschmidt, the limits of nerve poisoning for large fish at the end of the food chain, such as shark or swordfish, are expected to be increased from one to two milligrams of mercury per kilogram of fish for "economic policy reasons".
However, large predators are already so heavily loaded with mercury that about 50 per cent of the catches cannot be sold on the basis of the limits still in force.
After doubling the limits, only 14.5 percent would be non-sellable.
In return for this loosening, the EU wants to tighten the limit values for other fish from currently 0.5 milligrams to 0.1 milligrams of mercury per kilogram, according to Foodwatch.
However, Foodwatch referred to this as a “trick” because smaller fried fish, such as carp, are usually so low-loaded that they already comply with the planned peaks today.
The decline in small fish is therefore "a perfidious distraction that only helps the economy," Wolfschmidt said.
Mercury is a highly toxic heavy metal for humans, which is highly enriched through the food chain, especially in predators.
The federal government therefore warns that "already small amounts can cause unborn damage to the nervous system".
The Federal Ministry of the Environment on its homepage, however, explains that a "health hazard to the general population" is not expected.
Mercury enters the environment mainly through the combustion of coal.
According to a written information from the Federal Ministry of the Environment, the German coal power plants are pumping out more than six tons of mercury per year, two thirds of the total amount emitted in Germany.
The concentration of mercury in fish in Elbe, the Rhine and the Danube, for example, was “permanently exceeded and extensively,” the “mirror” quoted in March from the paper.
Last year, European-wide warnings against mercury in fish were already among the most frequently reported health risks in the EU’s RASFF warning system.
Foodwatch calls consumers to protest against EU plans at: www.quecksilber-aktion.foodwatch.de
